    "narrative": "The clear engine of the LawDog offense today is **Jos\u00e9 Ram\u00edrez**, who boasts an elite 86.34 score against Lopez. His massive upside is fueled by a +10% park factor and a +13% SP skill advantage, making him a lock for the middle of the order. Following closely behind, **Lawrence Butler** (69.01) provides significant value from the bottom of the order, benefiting from a highly favorable park factor (+10%) and dynamic platoon advantage (+13%) against Cecconi. While **Will Smith** (66.35) and **Geraldo Perdomo** (63.70) are solid pillars today, look for **Perdomo** to outperform his base projection given his efficiency in the #2 hole against Imanaga.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was leaving **Yainer Diaz** (48.05) out of the lineup. He was the final cut, primarily due to the -19% SP skill penalty against Early, which outweighed the marginal gains from wind conditions. While **Jung Hoo Lee** (44.72) and **Matt Chapman** (43.47) were considered, they were ultimately benched because their matchup against Jax presents too much risk compared to our active starters. We are prioritizing efficiency over raw potential today to protect our game caps.\n\nThere is minimal weather-related risk on the slate, but we are monitoring the lineup health for **Gleyber Torres** and **Wenceel Perez**, both of whom are projected at 52.65 and 47.22 respectively. Both face Rocker, and while the platoon splits have created some volatility in their projections, their ability to navigate the late-inning situations makes them viable starts. Keep a close watch on **Jeremiah Jackson**, as his score of 44.79 is anchored by the potential for a stolen base against Weathers, which remains a focal point of our strategy even when his overall offensive floor looks thin.",
